    {
      "id": "GENUS_SARCOPHILUS",
      "name": "Sarcophilus",
      "rank": "GENUS",
      "description": "The Tasmanian devil — the world's largest carnivorous marsupial, and one of the most charismatic endangered animals on Earth. Devils are powerfully built scavengers and hunters with the strongest bite force relative to body size of any living mammal, capable of consuming every part of a carcass including dense bones. They are intensely social scavengers, communicating their hierarchical status with blood-curdling screams and communal feeding rituals. Mainland devils were driven extinct around 3,000 years ago following the introduction of dingoes; they survived on Tasmania where dingoes never arrived. Since 1996, devil facial tumour disease — one of only three known transmissible cancers — has killed over 80% of the Tasmanian population. Conservation breeding programs and reintroductions to mainland Australia (where dingoes have been excluded) offer hope.",
      "lineage": "Tasmanian Devil",
