    {
      "id": "GENUS_ANTECHINUS",
      "name": "Antechinus",
      "rank": "GENUS",
      "description": "Antechinuses — small, mouse-like marsupials of Australian forest, famous for one of the most extreme reproductive strategies of any mammal. In every species, all males die after a frenzied two-week mating season. Males suppress their immune system, stop producing blood cells, and experience the equivalent of a catastrophic cortisol-driven stress collapse — their fur falls out, they bleed internally, and they continue mating even as they are literally dying. All males are dead before the young are born. This 'suicidal reproduction' is thought to be an adaptation to a narrow window of insect abundance — with no males surviving to compete for food, the females and young have exclusive access to the peak resource.",
      "lineage": "Antechinuses",
      "children": [
